  "prompt": "Why do people open same business side by side?",
  "response": "People open similar businesses side by side for several reasons:\n\n1. Market demand\n- High customer traffic\n- Proven business model\n- Good location with potential customers\n\n2. Competition benefits\n- Attracts more customers to the area\n- Creates comparison opportunities\n- Encourages business improvement\n\n3. Economic factors\n- Low entry barriers\n- Similar startup costs\n- Perceived low risk\n\n4. Clustering effect\n- Convenience for customers\n- Sharing infrastructure\n- Learning from each other's strategies\n\n5. Cultural/traditional practices\n- Some communities have traditional business clusters\n- Familiar business patterns\n- Historical economic development\n\n6. Local zoning regulations\n- Certain areas designated for specific business types\n- Affordable commercial spaces\n\n7. Psychological reasons\n- Follow successful business models\n- Perceived lower risk\n- Sense of community among similar businesses\n\n8. Economic opportunities\n- Similar profit margins\n- Proven business success\n- Stable income potential\n\nExamples include restaurant rows, car dealership districts, shopping centers with multiple similar stores.\n\nWhile it might seem counterintuitive, having multiple similar businesses can actually create a beneficial ecosystem that attracts more customers and promotes healthy competition.",
